segments.text: One thing I found out was I was never in a hurry to get back to A&M on Sundays.
And I don't think anybody else was.
It was, you know, you're proud of your school, you're proud of A&M and everything, but A&M on Sundays was not, there was nothing going on here.
And so we, you know, there was things going on in Houston.
I remember

Jones Hall, as a matter of fact, I even have some tickets where we would, on Sundays, we'd go to Sunday afternoon matinees at Jones Hall, and there would be entertainers there, Peter, Paul, and Mary, Johnny Mathis.
And on Saturday night, would there also sometimes be a big dance at the Rice or something like that?
Well, you know, I don't recall going to that, what happened,
what happened was my high school would, you know, 98% of my high school went to Texas.
Lamar High School people went to Texas.
Or maybe SMU or TCU or Baylor, you know, but they didn't go to A&M.
And most, there was a large number of my high school that I'd gone to elementary school, junior high school, and high school with, and so it seemed like my high school guys
would come back, would be back in town, and we would have high school parties, and I would invite my Aggie friends to those high school parties.
I think Ginny's here.
She'll catch it.
But I don't remember Aggie-focused parties that I went to.
Now, at Fort Worth, it was different.
Describe that court trip.
Well, at the Fort Worth court trip, it was TCU, of course, we were playing.
I was not from Fort Worth.
I didn't know anything about Fort Worth, so it was a reversal of roles.
And so I stayed at somebody's house, and his name was Mike Bryan, Fish Bryan.
I stayed at Mike's house, but because I was dating Jeannie, I didn't.
I didn't date anybody up there, so I don't recall going to the parties afterwards.
And I think the TCU game that year was a night game, so it wasn't over until 10.30 or so.
In your four years, do you remember any kind of negative event as a part of the parade, the march?
Did the audience ever behave negatively?
No.
Matter of fact, I've marched all over the world in all kinds of situations, and I've never had an incident where anybody threw anything at us, and certainly at that point in time didn't.
There was a lot of people down there, and the core marching...
It's impressive to this day.
It was impressive then.
It's always commanded respect.
Yeah, so I don't recall any shenanigans at all.
That fall, while all this is going on, were you going to class regularly?
Oh, yeah.
Because I was not a good student, I mean, I wasn't a natural student, I never missed class.
And I was always on time, and I always did my homework regularly.
you know, to the best of my abilities.
And that's what a lot of times would get me from a C to a B.
Did you have any rules about where you sat in the room?
Front or the back?
I didn't sit either one.
I wasn't a front row, you know, I wasn't a spring butt.
But I wasn't a rear-rank Rudy either.
I think...
Wait a minute.
Rear-rank?
Rear-rank Rudy.
Rudy?
Rudy.
R-U-D-Y?
Yeah, that's the little guys.
In the formation, back in the old days.
Now, I changed it.
When I became an officer, I didn't form my... See, the way you'd form a company at A&M was...
except for the seniors and juniors, everybody else marched by size and you formed up from the right side and so from the left guide and so I was always the right rear guy, rear rank Rudy and so
When I got in the real army, I wouldn't let my first sergeant size the men.
I would march them by squads and keep them in squad integrity.
My formations never looked quite as sharp as the Aggies, but I always felt that squad integrity was more important than looks.
Were you all in the era when classes and or instructors had nicknames?
Well, it may have been, but I don't recall.
It's about that time that they started ending.
Yeah, I don't recall.
I was raised where authority was authority, and as long as the professor did what he was supposed to do, he commanded authority, and I wasn't.
I wasn't going to do anything to that authority.
The faculty members were always there to teach?
Yeah.
And if you needed to see one in his or her office, they were available?
They were.
Matter of fact, I was impressed.
I wasn't a good student, a great student, and I wasn't a bad student.
So I was kind of in the middle of the road.
So I didn't have an occasion to need a lot of meetings.
But I remember some professors made you.
have a one-on-one with them.
And you got a card and you had a time.
And I thought that was a good technique because I did like my chemistry class.
It was 200 or 300 in my chemistry class my freshman year.
And I didn't like that.
I liked 30-man classrooms where you could identify with a professor.
Because, kind of like football, the reason I got to play was not because of my talent, but because of my heart.
The coaches, I mean, I knew all my plays.
I practiced.
I was always there, always on time, and I gave it my all.
It's just I didn't have the natural talents that other people had.
But they would play me just because...
I would die before I let anybody down.
Well, in a small classroom, a professor would figure out that I always did my homework, I was always prepared, and I was honest, and I would do everything I could.
It's just that I wasn't a gifted student.
But in a big classroom, it was just numbers, and you were at a disadvantage.
And so I did like it when you got to meet instructors and start some kind of a personal relationship.
And you didn't have any teaching assistants.
You had real faculty members.
I don't ever remember a teaching assistant.

Now, what I do remember, you know, later on, and we'll get to that, I guess, was all the international students that A&M had and how impressed I was with that because they were from Pakistan, they were from Saudi Arabia, they were from all over, a lot of them in agriculture.
And I thought that was kind of neat that A&M was doing that.
I didn't realize at the time what a big program it was and how important it was.
It's just that I thought it was neat that here this Texas Agriculture School had all these foreign students.
And the foreign students were all very dedicated and hardworking, and I kind of enjoyed interacting with them.
All right, another big ritual bonfire.
What did you do with bonfire your freshman year?
Nothing.
We didn't have one.
Kennedy was shot, and I was passing Henderson Hall, going to dorm night 17, and one of the Melton twins, and I never could tell them apart, ran out and said, Randy,
have you heard what happened in Dallas?"
And I said, no.
And he said, President Kennedy has been shot dead.
And I know exactly where I was.
And I said, you know, and I started thinking about it, you know, assassinations and what I'd read and history and everything.
You know, and I asked a bunch of questions and it was on the radio.
We went into Harrison Hall and they were talking about it.
And then the next day or that same day, you know, General Rutter announced there would be no bonfire that year.
So my Thanksgiving, November of 63, there was no bonfire.
Now, we did play Texas University and we played them at home and they were rated number one in the nation.
And at the end of the first half, we were winning 21-0.
We were outscored 24-21.
But there was no bonfire.
Now, there had been some cutting done.
Yeah, right.
But you and your outfit were not involved at that point.
Well, I was helping with the chainsaw crew because I was a flatheader, and they knew it.

my reputation, you know, being on this farm and having a pine tree farm that, you know, and I had a 26-pound McCullough chainsaw, and so they were logging hardwood just south of here, and when they would bring them up, and the bonfire then was behind Sabisa.
It wasn't over where the accident was, and so I don't remember as a company project.
I just remember being singled out
And the couple days before, I was sizing logs, and I was showing people how to do that and whatever.
And I kind of liked that because I was a fish, and I knew more about what we were doing than anybody that around.
And there was a lot of upperclassmen, but they didn't know what they were doing.
And I'd run a chainsaw since I was 10 or 11 years old.
Had you all cut?
any down or many down?

Well I wasn't cutting them somebody else was cutting them and they were bringing them in and we were sizing them and saying okay these were going to be the base logs and we wanted them 32 feet long and so we were measuring and I was cutting them 32 feet or whatever it was and then okay these logs are smaller we'll have those for the second deck and then we want that to be you know 24 feet long and so I was cutting and then the logs would come in 26 feet
and you'd have to cut two feet off the small end.
And so I was thinking that part of the bonfire was already erected, wasn't it?
Well, I don't remember that.
I remember my mission was I was cutting logs away from where
the center pole was.
I know the center pole was in place because that was done early.
And the others were still on.
Yeah, but I don't remember the crane yet hauling anything because in subsequent years, see, I was in charge of the bonfire chainsaws.
And so when I was, my junior and senior year was one of the few people that caught on the stacks.
Describe that.
Well, back then, we didn't stand the bonfire straight up.
They were angled in.
Now you gotta understand that everybody that worked around the bonfire, that really worked around the logs, were farm boys or people that kind of understood those kind of things.
They weren't engineers, but we understood
heavy equipment and the dangers.
I remember how important it was that the center post be stout and properly bolted.
I remember even being part of the packing crew that would pack and make sure the center pole was strong.
My job was to pick the initial logs that would become the critical

logs that the first base logs would build around, and so we would bring all the base logs in, the biggest of the trees, and we'd put those, categorize them, and then I'd study them, and then we would, you know, I was, this was my junior year, you know, I said, okay, let's use that one, and so then they would bring that up, and we would drag it up with the tractor, and then the crane would lift it up,

and we would lean it into the post, and we'd put one in, and then put one on the 180, and then put one on the 180, and we'd fill up that first, oh, about eight logs, and then we would start filling on top.
Well, on the sides, when we got to where we, where whoever was in charge thought that was enough, and we would start to build the second deck, a selected few of us
we'd get on the crane, we'd put our foot in the hook, and we'd have the chainsaw in one hand, and we would go up on the second deck, or on the first deck, and we were the flatheaders.
And we would cut off to make the tabletop, because even though we had measured all the logs, when you leaned them, you ended up with long and short logs.
And so what you wanted for your second deck was as flat as you could, so we went in there

and but but uh back then uh we all matter of fact we all talked about you know what happens if it falls and we all had plans so i'm gonna ride this log down i'm gonna grab for the hook uh or whatever but there was only three to five of us ever allowed and and it was and the people up there were all uh knowledgeable of um heavy equipment chainsaws
You know, we wore the right kind of boots.
And no hijinks.
And there was, no.
Up there.
No, this was all serious because this was very dangerous and we knew it.
And were you all working 24 hours a day?
Yeah, they had us floodlights out there.
And I think my junior year I did most of the night shift.
My senior year I did most of the day shift.
About how many weeks did you and the others work on that?
I remember it being a long time.
Was it?
It was a couple of weeks for sure.
But it wasn't a month or two?
Oh, no, no, no.
It got real serious just the week before.
And I used to think...
if I was in charge, I could be better organized and shorten the time because it was taking you away from classes and a lot of competing things.
And I felt the bonfire was important, but I always felt that if it was better organized, it could be done in a shorter period of time.
But I did always think that none of the bonfires that I was involved in ever fell prematurely.
And did you all have a prejudged
size.
Yeah, matter of fact I have pictures of the bonfire and it was only you know.
You weren't trying to build it bigger than ever before.
No, no I don't know when that started.

That started after I left that every year it had to be bigger than the year before because ours I think was three decks, three decks of big logs and then maybe a fourth deck of just a few logs and that were cabled together.
You can see the cable, I've got the pictures but
I don't know when the zealousness started of, I don't know when it started of standing them straight up, because I could have told them that was not going to work.
And I don't know when they started making it so high.
And that all happened after 67.
Now, who was actually in charge of Bonfire?
There was a cadet, and it wasn't Eddie Joe Davis.
I mean, it wasn't, you know, Eddie Joe was our corps commander.
It wasn't him.
There was a designated guy, and it was somebody, you kind of grew into that position, and it had nothing to do with corps leadership or whatever.
What was kind of neat about the bonfire, they figured out that they better have people who knew what they were doing, so they
your core positions didn't count.
They were looking for the talent of people that had done things like that growing up.
In your four years of working on Bonfire.
Three years, yeah.
Three.
What is the worst accident that you remember?
I do not remember an accident.
Even a smashed finger or anything.
Really?
Nobody broke a leg?
No, I don't remember any accident.
On my watch...
where I was involved, there was never an accident.
We could have sprained an ankle or something, but nobody ever said anything about it.
As far as you know, what kind of drinking and hijinks went on out?
Well, what was interesting was all my friends and everybody knew that I didn't drink.
And they knew I didn't really like to be around drinkers.
So it just didn't happen around me.
I didn't see it.
I knew it was going on, but it wasn't.
The guys that were working on the bonfire, I mean, this was serious business to us.
And I think the guys that were probably drinking
were the guys that, the wannabes that wished they knew what they were doing couldn't, and so they were out there just fooling around.
But they stayed, you know, away outside the crane, outside the bulldozers.
I mean, inside that ring, I always felt was a fairly disciplined group of guys.
And there were no, there were so few co-eds.
I never saw a co-ed on the bonfire in my three years.
And there weren't any women hanging around.
No.
So it was a,
No, it was, no.
You know, you never know for sure, and I guess somebody could remind you of something you don't remember, but, you know, I've read the accident report.
I was in Pacific when, and I read all the stuff on the webpage, and I don't remember any of that kind of stuff going on.
Right, so you go home Thanksgiving and Christmas, and then get your grades the first semester.
You passed everything.
Yeah, I did okay the first semester.
I mean, I did pretty good, really.
So you're still planning on veterinary medicine, second semester.
How did the spring semester go?
Well, I found out
that I was a better fall student.
All my fall semesters, the grades were much better than the spring semesters.
Is there any reason?
I think I get spring fever.
I thought I, as soon as winter was over and it started being spring, you know, I was ready to head to the woods again.
You know, I mean, I was, I just, and that's the only thing I can remember because
I just reviewed all, I've got all my transcripts from, and the only, you know, the exception to that was graduate school.
I made all As in graduate school, but by that time I was an Army captain, and I was told, you're representing the U.S. Army, and so I made all As in graduate school.
But at A&M, I made good grades in the fall, and I made okay grades in the spring.
All right, then you go home, and what did you do that first summer?
I went to Carrizo Springs and I worked at my uncle's ranch all summer long.
Six dollars a day, room and board.
We were awake at 4.30.
We would have the horses saddled by 5.30 and we worked cattle all summer.
And the funniest story on that one, and I love it, was I came back and I didn't shave or get a haircut all summer.
And I never left the ranch.
The ranch was 70,000 acres.
And I went down there, and I never left the ranch for three months.
And I was the junior cowboy, so I always was bringing up the rear of all the cattle drives.
And I always had the dirty jobs.
And so I chose not to shave.
And I didn't grow a pretty beard, but I grew a beard after three months.
And I came back, my cousin, who went to my first cousin, one of my first cousins, and one of my dearest friends, was accepted to vet school.
And so he, his name was Donald Dauron from Louisiana, and he'd gone to Southwestern in Lafayette and was accepted to A&M Vet School.
He was a native Cajun.
So he's married, too.
And they're living over in the World War II barracks that had an unsavory name, but I loved the name.
I mean, because it was where all the married people lived back then.
And so I had talked to Donald from the ranch, and he was already here, because vet students had to be here a little early.
And he was going to start vet school.
So they had gotten this apartment.
They were living on the first floor of one of those old army barracks.
And so I drove up in my pickup truck and I'd never met his wife.
And this is one of my closest cousins, but he'd gotten married and I'd just never met Marie.
So I knocked on the door and I got a beard on and long hair and cowboy boots and blue jeans.
And she says, oh, I'm glad you're here.
The problem is under the sink.
And so I followed her.
And I said, well, and so I said, she said, don't you have some tools?
And I said, well, they're in my truck, but I want to see what the problem is.
I mean, I loved it.
And so she said, it's just leaking at that turn under the sink.
And I said, well, let me look at it, and then I'll know what tools to bring.
So she opens up under the sink, and I crawl under the sink.
Well, about that time, Donald walks in the kitchen, and I come out from under the sink, and he says, Randy, what are you doing under the sink?
And Marie says, that's not Randy, that's the plumber.
And he says, no, no, that's my cousin Randy.
And to this day, it's the biggest laugh that my darling Marie and I have.
But no, I cowboyed all summer.
I went to, you know, and just, we worked seven days a week,
And you're still at that point determined to be a veterinarian?
Right, and I was vaccinating and doing all the cutting and doing all the veterinary type work down there on the ranch.
How was being a sophomore at A&M different from being a freshman?
Well, you're a new outfit.
Yeah, I'm in B1 now over in the new core area and Mickey Ballard is our company commander.
And I'm a sophomore.
It's sad to say I didn't take the Corps real serious.
I was taking the ROTC courses, and there was two officers over there, Captain Bolting, who died in Vietnam,
and Captain Jim Simmons, who retired as Lieutenant Colonel and is still a lifelong friend of mine, they were instructors and I was real impressed with them.
And so I was serious about ROTC, but I wasn't a serious Corps guy.
I just, I kind of tolerated it, you know, because to be honest, and you can read in my journals, it wasn't anything that I disliked.
I just had
so many interests.
I mean, I was still rodeo clowning.
I was still calf roping.
I was running this ranch.
You know, I was playing music, playing guitar.
I had so many interests that, and then I was, and this was my home all around here.
I mean, I knew everybody in every town.
And, and, you know, so many of the people were from your shoe in the, in the valley and, and, and, and the A&M was their family.
But for me,
Off post was my family.
I never caused any trouble.
I did everything I was supposed to do, but my heart wasn't in it.
I remember as a sophomore, your mission was you had to teach the fish all these things.
I chose to teach them like a couple of my football coaches that I liked.
I was treating them totally with dignity and respect.
and was telling them why and was talking to them pretty natural.
And I remember one of the juniors called me in and says, you have to holler at them.
And I said, okay, I mean, I can, but that's not my style.
And I said, I think they'll see through it very quickly.
And he says, no, you've got to, you know, you're just not tough enough on the fish.
And I said, well, let me do this.
You put me responsible for some fish.
and tell me what they're supposed to do.
And after a few weeks, let's evaluate my fish to somebody who's been hollering at them.
Well, he didn't take me up on it, because I think he knew that I would coddle them and bring them around and everything.
So I was an upperclassman.
who never really harassed the fish, but, you know, interacted with them and tried to teach them, you know, the important things about A&M.
And there was some, you know, there was some really great things that I felt that by the time I was a sophomore that I understood that they needed to understand.
And who was the commandant at that era?
Baker, Colonel Baker.
is who I remember.
What was your impression and remembrance of him?
He was a crusty colonel, and if you didn't screw up, you never had the scene.
If you just did your job, you could... And I was kind of that way.
Matter of fact, I never met General Rutter personally because the only people that met General Rutter were really good students and really bad students.
and I was in between.
But what did you in general, what did you and all of your closest buddies, what was your impression of him as a person?
Colonel Baker?
No, Rutter.
Oh, I mean he was on a pedestal.
Matter of fact, when I remember I was in distinct minority
And as a sophomore, my sophomore year is when the first women came to A&M, 64.
Yeah, talk about the attitude you all had, you and your contemporaries, about those changes.
Well, I remember I was in the minority in that I thought it was a good thing.
And one of the reasons I thought it was a good thing was because I had read that General Rutter was a proponent of it and felt it was important to the future
of the now university.
Because at the same time, we went from a college to a university.
And he did both of those things.
And he was criticized and credited with both of them.
But because he did them, matter of fact, there was a big debate was, I'm going to have AMC on my ring.
And I said, well, if I ever get a ring, I'm going to have Texas A&M University.
And it was all because of General Rutter.
I met him, and I'd like to tell that story.
I met him on my way to Vietnam.
I had gone through all my schooling.
I'd gone to the 82nd Airborne and jumped out of airplanes for a while.
The Army called up.
They saw that I was a pilot with a lot of hours.
And I think it was in my records how I'd done in elementary flight training.
So the Army called up and asked me to go to flight school.
And I said, whatever y'all want me to do.
And so I went to flight school.
Well, I was going to Vietnam in December of 69.
And I was really, you know, my intent
was to go to Vietnam, serve my country, come back and try to get back in vet school.
So Dr. Wooten was my, because I graduated in ag eco, which was a natural thing for a veterinary and medicine guy to do.

So Dr. Wooten was my advisor, and so I was on leaving Houston en route to Vietnam, and I called him from Houston, and he said, well, Ray, why don't you come up and let's talk about what you want to do a year from now.
Because, you know, I was just going to serve my country and go back to college, go back to, you know, some kind of graduate school and try to get back in or try to get in vet school.
Well, so I'm up here to see Dr. Wooten, and he said, so he said,
